    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Bargaining Phrases and Comparisons",
      "explanation": "Bargaining is common in Indonesian markets and small shops. The key phrase is 'Berapa harganya?' (How much is it?). To say something is 'too' expensive, use 'terlalu': 'terlalu mahal' (too expensive). To make comparisons, use 'lebih' (more): 'lebih murah' (cheaper/more cheap). To ask 'Is there...?', use 'Ada...?': 'Ada yang lebih murah?' (Is there something cheaper?). 'Bisa kurang?' literally means 'Can it be less?' and is the classic bargaining phrase. You can also suggest a price: 'Bagaimana kalau...' (How about...) followed by your offer.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "That's too expensive!",
          "target_primary": "Itu terlalu mahal!",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Can you lower the price?",
          "target_primary": "Bisa kurang?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "How about thirty thousand?",
          "target_primary": "Bagaimana kalau tiga puluh ribu?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "I'll take it.",
          "target_primary": "Saya ambil.",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Bargaining in Indonesian Markets",
      "content": "Bargaining (tawar-menawar) is an integral part of shopping at traditional markets (pasar) and street vendors in Indonesia. In general, fixed-price stores like malls and supermarkets do not allow bargaining, but at markets, souvenir shops, and with street vendors, it is expected. A common approach is to offer about 50-60% of the asking price and negotiate from there. Always bargain with a smile and a friendly attitude -- it should feel like a pleasant social exchange, not a confrontation. If you say 'Bisa kurang?' with a smile, most sellers will happily negotiate. Key tip: if you name a price and the seller agrees, you are expected to buy the item -- walking away after agreeing on a price is considered rude. Learning to say numbers confidently makes the whole experience much smoother."
    }
